(2877, NULL, 'help.page.gamemanifest', '<h3>Game manifest</h3>\n<p>A game manifest consists of:</p>\n<ul>\n    <li>name &ndash; the name of the game manifest; you choose e.g. the name of the game model in combination with the name of the playground.</li>\n    <li>game model - the name of the game model you use; be aware: once you have chosen this, you can not change it for reasons of consistency; delete if necessary the game manifest and create a new one.</li>\n    <li>playground - the name of the used playground.</li>\n    <li>number of roles &ndash; the number of roles that exist in the used game model (will be automatically entered).</li>\n    <li>status &ndash; a game manifest that is not yet finished will get automatically the status &ldquo;under construction&rdquo;; you complete it by giving it a status &ldquo;Personal&rdquo;; you hand it over by giving it the status &ldquo;Public&rdquo; (this is only possible if the game model also has the status &ldquo;Public&rdquo;).</li>\n    <li>roles &ndash; as soon as the game model is set, a list of roles appears on screen; you can then choose a playground object for every role.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>When you give a game manifest the status &ldquo;Personal&rdquo;, you can have game sessions on that basis.&nbsp; As long as that exist, you can view and copy the game manifest, but not edit it. You can also give your game model the status &ldquo;Public&rdquo;. Then you hand it over to the publisher who gives it to a third party or lets them use it under certain conditions.</p>', 1),
